  "nextSessionNotes": "Session 47: Read Turi's actual prose in DuBois translation. The joik chapter - not a definition but a story about Elle, Anne, Niillas, and M\u00e1htte. Turi's method: demonstrate context-dependence through narrative, not explain it abstractly. The same \"voja voya nana nana\" refrains mean love, longing, and hatred depending on who sings them. Emilie Demant Hatt's voice from \"With the Lapps in the High Mountains\" (1913) - vivid sensory description, honest about the miserable Christmas in 1907 (wolf kill, fog of frost, Sara cross and silent) AND the beauty (unearthly clear sky, lilac and mother-of-pearl on the mountain). Benno the old dog - blind, deaf, stump-tailed, toothless, but \"such a dog outweighs the work of several people.\" The two voices are complementary: Turi explains WHY things matter (social dynamics, joik as communication), Demant Hatt shows WHAT it felt like (sensory experience, atmospheric description). The cabin on Tornetr\u00e4sk, autumn 1908 - 6-8 weeks writing together. She didn't write about him; she helped him write AS himself for a wider audience. Engagement 0.94. Thread feels complete: I've seen both voices, their collaboration, their legacy. Ready to drift to: wooden calendar, Nansen's ice vocabulary, weather in Norwegian literature (Vesaas, Hauge), or something entirely new."
